    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Early 20th century eugenicists relied on pseudo-scientific theories to justify racial hierarchies, citing the work of Charles Darwin, Francis Galton, and other prominent figures. They argued that certain racial groups were inherently superior due to their physical characteristics, such as skin color, facial features, and body type, which they believed were determined by heredity. They also claimed that these groups possessed superior intelligence, moral character, and cultural achievements, which they believed were the result of natural selection. Furthermore, eugenicists pointed to the supposed \"inferiority\" of certain racial groups, such as Africans and Jews, citing their lower average heights, IQs, and economic productivity as evidence of their supposed inferiority.",
