    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Eugenicists often cited flawed and outdated studies, such as those by Galton's \"Hereditary Genius\" (1869) and the work of Madison Grant's \"The Passing of the Great Race\" (1916). They claimed that IQ scores were heritable and that certain racial groups had average IQs that were significantly lower than others. For example, they cited the work of William Stern's 1912 study, which supposedly showed that Jews had an average IQ of 100.8, compared to 115 for Germans and 138 for Scandinavians. They also pointed to the supposed \"physical\" differences between racial groups, such as the supposedly smaller brain size of Africans compared to Europeans.\n\nThey also relied on the idea of \"regression to the mean,\" claiming that individuals from supposedly \"inferior\" groups would, over time, \"regress\" to the mean and become more like the supposedly superior groups through intermarriage and assimilation. They also claimed that certain racial groups were more prone to certain diseases, such as syphilis, which they believed was a sign of \"racial degeneracy.\"",
      "source": "target",
